# DAST Scanner

Performs runtime vulnerability detection on running web applications using Nuclei and OWASP ZAP. Detects OWASP Top 10 vulnerabilities that static analysis misses.

## When to Use

- The user provides a target URL or Docker Compose file to security-test
- Dynamic (black-box) testing of a running application is needed
- Detecting OWASP Top 10 vulnerabilities at runtime
- Chaining after `grimsec-repo-analyzer` has deployed the target app
- Nuclei scans, ZAP scans, or combined DAST reports are requested

## ⚠️ IMPORTANT: Authorization Required

**Never run active scans against production systems without explicit authorization.** Always confirm scope with the user before executing full or API scan modes.

ZAP active scans are loud and will appear in access logs.

## Pipeline Overview

```
Phase 1: Environment Setup + Target Discovery (httpx)
Phase 2: Nuclei Quick Scan (CVE templates, misconfigs, exposures)
Phase 3: ZAP Deep Scan (spider/crawl, active scan, passive scan)
Phase 4: Finding Correlation (deduplicate, map to CWE/OWASP)
Phase 5: Report Generation (unified dast-report.md)
```

## Severity Mapping

| Severity | Finding Types |
|----------|--------------|
| CRITICAL | RCE, confirmed SQL injection, authentication bypass |
| HIGH | Stored XSS, SSRF, path traversal, IDOR, reflected XSS with DOM sink |
| MEDIUM | Missing CSP/HSTS headers, CORS misconfiguration, information disclosure |
| LOW | Cookie without Secure/HttpOnly flags, clickjacking, version disclosure |

## Phase 1 — Environment Setup

Check tool availability:
```bash
which nuclei && nuclei -version
docker image inspect ghcr.io/zaproxy/zaproxy:stable >/dev/null 2>&1
```

Install Nuclei if missing:
```bash
# macOS/Linux
curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/projectdiscovery/nuclei/main/install.sh | bash
# Or via Go
go install github.com/projectdiscovery/nuclei/v3/cmd/nuclei@latest
```

Pull ZAP Docker image:
```bash
docker pull ghcr.io/zaproxy/zaproxy:stable
```

Install httpx for target discovery:
```bash
go install github.com/projectdiscovery/httpx/cmd/httpx@latest
```

Create output directory:
```bash
mkdir -p dast-results
```

## Phase 2 — Target Discovery

```bash
httpx -u <TARGET_URL> -tech-detect -status-code -title -json -o dast-results/httpx.json
```

Review detected technologies — use them to select Nuclei template categories.

## Phase 3 — Nuclei Quick Scan

```bash
nuclei -u <TARGET_URL> \
  -t cves,misconfiguration,exposures,technologies,default-logins \
  -severity critical,high,medium \
  -json-export dast-results/nuclei.json \
  -rate-limit 100 \
  -timeout 300
```

**Template categories by tech stack:**
- Web frameworks (Django, Rails, Laravel): use `cves`, `exposures`, `technologies`
- Admin panels: use `default-logins`, `exposures`
- APIs: use `misconfiguration`, `cves`

Review CRITICAL/HIGH findings immediately — they may warrant escalation before ZAP completes.

## Phase 4 — ZAP Deep Scan

**ZAP scan modes:**
- `baseline` — fast passive scan (CI/CD safe, ~2 min)
- `full` — active + passive scan (comprehensive, ~20–60 min)
- `api` — OpenAPI/SOAP/GraphQL-aware scan

```bash
# Baseline scan (safe for any environment)
docker run -t ghcr.io/zaproxy/zaproxy:stable \
  zap-baseline.py -t <TARGET_URL> \
  -J dast-results/zap-baseline.json

# Full active scan (requires explicit authorization)
docker run -t ghcr.io/zaproxy/zaproxy:stable \
  zap-full-scan.py -t <TARGET_URL> \
  -J dast-results/zap-full.json

# API scan with OpenAPI spec
docker run -t ghcr.io/zaproxy/zaproxy:stable \
  zap-api-scan.py -t <TARGET_URL> \
  -f openapi -s \
  -J dast-results/zap-api.json
```

**For authenticated scans**, add login configuration:
```bash
docker run -t ghcr.io/zaproxy/zaproxy:stable \
  zap-full-scan.py -t <TARGET_URL> \
  --hook /path/to/auth-hook.py \
  -J dast-results/zap-full.json
```

## Phase 5 — Finding Correlation

1. Load both `dast-results/nuclei.json` and `dast-results/zap.json`
2. Deduplicate by matching: same host + port + path + vulnerability class (CWE)
3. For each deduplicated finding, assign:
   - `cwe_id` (e.g., CWE-89 for SQLi, CWE-79 for XSS)
   - `owasp_category` (e.g., A03:2021 — Injection)
   - `unified_severity` (use the higher of the two tool ratings)
   - `source_tools` list

## Phase 6 — Report Generation

Produce `dast-results/dast-report.md` with:
- Executive summary (total count by severity, top 3 critical findings)
- Finding table sorted by severity
- Per-finding details: endpoint, method, evidence, CWE, OWASP category
- Remediation recommendations
- Recommended immediate actions

## Inputs

| Input | Required |
|-------|----------|
| `TARGET_URL` | Yes |
| `inventory.json` from grimsec-repo-analyzer | No (auto-discovers) |
| OpenAPI spec | No (enables API scan mode) |
| Auth credentials | No (enables authenticated scan) |

## Output Files

| File | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `dast-results/nuclei.json` | Raw + parsed Nuclei findings |
| `dast-results/zap.json` | Raw + parsed ZAP findings |
| `dast-results/dast-report.md` | Unified DAST report |
| `dast-results/httpx.json` | Target discovery metadata |

## Tips

- Rate-limit Nuclei against fragile or production-adjacent targets: `--rate-limit 25`
- If target is only accessible via Docker internal networking, use `--network host`
- Nuclei template updates pull from the internet — use `--offline-mode` in air-gapped environments
- ZAP active scans against APIs: pass `--openapi-spec path/to/openapi.yaml` for better coverage
